            {
              "id": "07e7f5c3-613b-3993-91c0-aa3561c3a8a0",
              "name": "SQL Injection Vulnerability via JWT 'kid' Header Data Concatenation",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe vulnerability in question is an SQL Injection vulnerability that occurs via the JSON Web Token (JWT) 'kid' header data concatenation in Java. This vulnerability arises when an attacker manipulates the 'kid' parameter in the JWT header to inject malicious SQL queries. The 'kid' parameter is used to select the correct key for verifying the JWT signature. If the 'kid' parameter is concatenated directly into an SQL query without proper sanitization or parameterization, it can lead to SQL Injection attacks.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, it is recommended to use parameterized queries or prepared statements instead of string concatenation to construct SQL queries. This ensures that user input is always treated as literal data and not part of the SQL command.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nHere is a recommended fix for the vulnerability using a PreparedStatement:\n\n```java\nString query = \"SELECT key FROM jwt_keys WHERE id = ?\";\nPreparedStatement stmt = connection.prepareStatement(query);\nstmt.setString(1, kid);\nResultSet rs = stmt.executeQuery();\n```\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code example requires the following library dependencies:\n\n- A JDBC driver, such as MySQL Connector/J for MySQL databases.\n- The `java.sql` package, which is included in the Java SE platform.\n\n## OWASP and CWE Resources\n\n- [OWASP SQL Injection Prevention Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/SQL_Injection_Prevention_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [CWE-89: Improper Neutralization of Special Elements used in an SQL Command ('SQL Injection')](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/89.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-89",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/89.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "8.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-89"
                ]
              }
