            {
              "id": "1aca0602-4b30-3f3d-bb65-18dad958e1b6",
              "name": "\"Host and Referer or Origin Header Comparison Used for CSRF Validation Instead of Anti-CSRF Token\"",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe vulnerability \"Host and Referer or Origin Header Comparison Used for CSRF Validation Instead of Anti-CSRF Token\" occurs when an application relies on the HTTP headers \"Host\", \"Referer\" or \"Origin\" to prevent Cross-Site Request Forgery (CSRF) attacks. These headers can be manipulated by an attacker, making the application vulnerable to CSRF attacks.\n\nIn the provided code snippet, the application is checking if the \"Referer\" header contains the \"Host\" header. If it does not, the application assumes that the request is a CSRF attack. However, an attacker can easily manipulate these headers to bypass this check.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nThe best way to prevent CSRF attacks is to use anti-CSRF tokens. These tokens are unique to each session and request, making it impossible for an attacker to guess or forge them. The application should generate a new anti-CSRF token for each session and include it in every state-changing request (e.g., a POST request). The server should then verify the token before processing the request.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\n```java\nimport javax.servlet.http.HttpServletRequest;\nimport javax.servlet.http.HttpSession;\n\n// ...\n\nString csrfToken = request.getParameter(\"csrfToken\");\nHttpSession session = request.getSession(false);\nif (session != null) {\n    String sessionToken = (String) session.getAttribute(\"csrfToken\");\n    if (csrfToken != null && csrfToken.equals(sessionToken)) {\n        // process the request\n    } else {\n        // reject the request\n    }\n} else {\n    // reject the request\n}\n```\n\nIn this code, the application retrieves the anti-CSRF token from the request and the session. It then compares the two tokens. If they match, the application processes the request. If they do not match or if the session does not exist, the application rejects the request.\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe provided code snippet does not require any additional library dependencies. It uses classes (`HttpServletRequest` and `HttpSession`) from the `javax.servlet.http` package, which is part of the Java Servlet API.\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP CSRF Prevention Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Cross-Site_Request_Forgery_Prevention_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [CWE-352: Cross-Site Request Forgery (CSRF)](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/352.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-352",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/352.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "8.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-352"
                ]
              }
