            {
              "id": "3ddf75c1-02bc-38b6-9d75-283c3953df9d",
              "name": "Direct JDBC Execution of Raw SQL in Method Parameter Vulnerability",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\n\"Direct JDBC Execution of Raw SQL in Method Parameter Vulnerability\" is a security vulnerability in Java programming language that occurs when an application uses user-supplied data in a SQL query without properly validating or escaping it. This can lead to SQL Injection attacks where an attacker can manipulate the SQL query to access, modify or delete data in the database.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, it is recommended to use parameterized queries or prepared statements instead of concatenating user-supplied data directly into a SQL query. This ensures that user-supplied data is always treated as literal values and not part of the SQL command.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nInstead of:\n\n```java\nString query = \"UPDATE users SET password='\" + newPassword + \"' WHERE username='\" + username + \"'\";\nstatement.executeUpdate(query);\n```\n\nUse:\n\n```java\nString query = \"UPDATE users SET password=? WHERE username=?\";\nPreparedStatement pstmt = connection.prepareStatement(query);\npstmt.setString(1, newPassword);\npstmt.setString(2, username);\npstmt.executeUpdate();\n```\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code example requires the following library dependencies:\n\n- `java.sql.Connection`\n- `java.sql.PreparedStatement`\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP SQL Injection Prevention Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/SQL_Injection_Prevention_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [CWE-89: Improper Neutralization of Special Elements used in an SQL Command ('SQL Injection')](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/89.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-89",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/89.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "8.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-89"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "3ef5f849-ac07-3b2c-ac3d-6ec7f337643d",
              "name": "\"Host and Referer or Origin Header Comparison Used for CSRF Validation Instead of Anti-CSRF Token\"",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe vulnerability arises when the application relies on the comparison of the \"Host\" and \"Referer\" or \"Origin\" HTTP headers for Cross-Site Request Forgery (CSRF) validation instead of using an anti-CSRF token. This approach is not secure because these headers can be manipulated by an attacker. \n\nAn attacker can exploit this vulnerability by tricking a victim into sending a request to the vulnerable application. Since the application only checks the \"Host\" and \"Referer\" or \"Origin\" headers, the attacker can forge these headers to bypass the CSRF protection.\n\n## Mitigation\n\nThe recommended way to prevent CSRF attacks is to use anti-CSRF tokens. These tokens are unique for each session and request, and they are unpredictable, making it difficult for an attacker to forge them.\n\n## Code Fix\n\nThe code should be modified to use an anti-CSRF token for CSRF validation. Here is an example of how to implement this in Java:\n\n```java\n// Generate a new anti-CSRF token\nString antiCSRFToken = UUID.randomUUID().toString();\n\n// Store the anti-CSRF token in the user's session\nrequest.getSession().setAttribute(\"antiCSRFToken\", antiCSRFToken);\n\n// Include the anti-CSRF token in the form\nout.println(\"<input type='hidden' name='antiCSRFToken' value='\" + antiCSRFToken + \"'>\");\n\n// Check the anti-CSRF token in the request against the one stored in the session\nif (!request.getParameter(\"antiCSRFToken\").equals(request.getSession().getAttribute(\"antiCSRFToken\"))) {\n    // The anti-CSRF tokens do not match - possible CSRF attack!\n    response.sendError(HttpServletResponse.SC_FORBIDDEN);\n    return;\n}\n```\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code example requires the following library dependencies:\n\n- Java Servlet API\n- Java UUID\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP CSRF Prevention Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Cross-Site_Request_Forgery_Prevention_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [CWE-352: Cross-Site Request Forgery (CSRF)](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/352.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-352",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/352.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "8.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-352"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "3eff988b-9d54-34e1-8800-5605601c94a9",
              "name": "Client-Supplied Total Trust Vulnerability",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\n\"Client-Supplied Total Trust Vulnerability\" is a security flaw that occurs when a program blindly trusts data supplied by the client without performing adequate validation or sanitization. In the context of Java programming, this vulnerability can lead to various security issues such as SQL Injection, Cross-Site Scripting (XSS), and Remote Code Execution (RCE) among others.\n\nIn the provided code snippet, the vulnerability arises from the fact that the program trusts the `QTY` and `Total` values supplied by the client. An attacker could manipulate these values to exploit the application.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, it is recommended to:\n\n1. Always validate and sanitize user-supplied input. Never trust data coming from the client.\n2. Use prepared statements with variable binding (also known as parameterized queries) when interacting with a database.\n3. Use appropriate response headers to prevent XSS attacks.\n4. Use the principle of least privilege. Only give necessary permissions to the users.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\n```java\ntry {\n    float qty = Float.parseFloat(QTY);\n    float total = Float.parseFloat(Total);\n\n    if (qty < 0 || total < 0) {\n        throw new IllegalArgumentException(\"QTY and Total must be positive.\");\n    }\n\n    if (qty * 2999.99 > total + 1) {\n        // ...\n    }\n} catch (NumberFormatException e) {\n    // Handle the exception\n} catch (IllegalArgumentException e) {\n    // Handle the exception\n}\n```\n\nIn the above code, we first parse the `QTY` and `Total` values to floats. If the parsing fails, a `NumberFormatException` is thrown which we catch and handle appropriately. We also check if the parsed values are negative and if so, we throw an `IllegalArgumentException`.\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe provided code snippet does not require any additional library dependencies to execute properly.\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP Top 10 - A1 Injection](https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/2017/A1_2017-Injection)\n- [CWE-20: Improper Input Validation](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/20.html)\n- [CWE-89: Improper Neutralization of Special Elements used in an SQL Command ('SQL Injection')](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/89.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-20",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/20.html"
                  },
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-89",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/89.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "5.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-20",
                  "CWE-89"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "3f26ea8b-1c50-3ac5-8544-286f9b413b18",
              "name": "\"Unsecured Actuator Endpoint in Application Code\"",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe \"Unsecured Actuator Endpoint in Application Code\" vulnerability refers to the exposure of sensitive information or functionality through actuator endpoints in a Spring Boot application. Actuator endpoints allow you to monitor and interact with your application. Spring Boot includes a number of built-in endpoints and lets you add your own. For example, the `health` endpoint provides basic application health information.\n\nIn the provided code, the `actuatorHealth()` method is mapped to the `/SecurityMisconfiguration/task3/actuator/health` URL and returns a JSON object with the status of the application and some other details. If this endpoint is not secured properly, it can be accessed by unauthorized users, potentially exposing sensitive information or allowing them to perform unwanted actions.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, you should secure your actuator endpoints. This can be done by restricting access to the endpoints to only authorized users or by disabling certain endpoints entirely if they are not needed. You can use Spring Security to secure your endpoints.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nYou can secure the actuator endpoints by adding Spring Security to your project and configuring it to restrict access to the endpoints. Here is an example of how to do this:\n\n```java\n@Configuration\npublic class ActuatorSecurity extends WebSecurityConfigurerAdapter {\n\n    @Override\n    protected void configure(HttpSecurity http) throws Exception {\n        http.requestMatcher(EndpointRequest.toAnyEndpoint()).authorizeRequests()\n            .anyRequest().hasRole(\"ACTUATOR\")\n            .and()\n            .httpBasic();\n    }\n\n}\n```\n\nIn this example, access to all actuator endpoints is restricted to users with the \"ACTUATOR\" role.\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe provided code requires the following library dependencies:\n\n- Spring Boot Starter Web\n- Spring Boot Starter Actuator\n- Spring Boot Starter Security\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP Top 10-2017 A6-Security Misconfiguration](https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/2017/A6_2017-Security_Misconfiguration)\n- [CWE-276: Incorrect Default Permissions](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/276.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-276",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/276.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "5.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-276"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "41f2a4c5-99fa-3da9-9976-7ed35f27ecef",
              "name": "Username or Email-Based Password Reset Vulnerability",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\n\"Username or Email-Based Password Reset Vulnerability\" is a security vulnerability that occurs when an application allows an attacker to reset the password of an account by knowing only the username or email address associated with that account. In the provided Java code snippet, the vulnerability arises from the fact that the unique code used for password reset is simply the reverse of the username. This makes it easy for an attacker to guess the unique code if they know the username, thereby gaining unauthorized access to the account.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, it is recommended to use a more secure method for generating the unique code used for password reset. The unique code should be random and unpredictable, and it should expire after a certain period of time or after it has been used. Additionally, the application should implement rate limiting to prevent an attacker from making too many password reset attempts in a short period of time.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nHere is a recommended fix for the provided code snippet:\n\n```java\nimport java.security.SecureRandom;\nimport java.math.BigInteger;\n\nSecureRandom random = new SecureRandom();\nString uniqueCode = new BigInteger(130, random).toString(32);\n\nif (uniqueCode.equals(StringUtils.reverse(username))) {\n    // ...\n}\n```\n\nIn this fix, the `java.security.SecureRandom` class is used to generate a random and unpredictable unique code. The `java.math.BigInteger` class is used to convert the random number to a string.\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe provided code snippet requires the following library dependencies:\n\n- Apache Commons Lang: This library provides the `StringUtils` class used in the code snippet.\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP Password Storage Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Password_Storage_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [OWASP Forgot Password Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Forgot_Password_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [CWE-640: Weak Password Recovery Mechanism for Forgotten Password](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/640.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-640",
