            {
              "id": "46225f11-2eee-3252-b7e4-5d0a44e491fb",
              "name": "Anti-CSRF Token Hardcoding Vulnerability",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nAnti-CSRF Token Hardcoding Vulnerability refers to a security flaw where the CSRF (Cross-Site Request Forgery) token, used to prevent CSRF attacks, is hardcoded into the application. This makes the application vulnerable to CSRF attacks as the token can be easily discovered and exploited by attackers. In the provided Java code, the CSRF token (`weakAntiCSRF`) is being compared with the request token (`validateReq`). If they are not equal, the request is considered invalid.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, avoid hardcoding CSRF tokens. Instead, generate a new token for each session or request. Store this token securely on the server side and include it as a hidden field in the form on the client side. When a form is submitted, compare the submitted token with the one stored on the server side. If they match, the request is valid; if not, reject the request.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\n```java\n// Generate a new CSRF token for each session\nString csrfToken = generateNewToken();\n\n// Store the token in the session\nrequest.getSession().setAttribute(\"csrfToken\", csrfToken);\n\n// In the form handling method\nString requestToken = request.getParameter(\"csrfToken\");\nString sessionToken = (String) request.getSession().getAttribute(\"csrfToken\");\n\nif (sessionToken == null || !sessionToken.equals(requestToken)) {\n    return failed(this).feedback(\"csrf-you-forgot-something\").build();\n}\n```\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code example does not specify any library dependencies. However, it is likely to require the following:\n\n- `javax.servlet-api` for handling HTTP requests and responses.\n- A library for generating CSRF tokens, such as `owasp-java-encoder`.\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP CSRF Prevention Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Cross-Site_Request_Forgery_Prevention_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [CWE-352: Cross-Site Request Forgery (CSRF)](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/352.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-352",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/352.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "8.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-352"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "4a70ecbb-a81e-34d2-8067-7cfb779485e5",
              "name": "\"SQL Injection Protection through Keyword Stripping and Space Blocking\"",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe code snippet provided is vulnerable to SQL Injection attacks. The vulnerability arises from the fact that the code is trying to prevent SQL Injection by stripping out certain SQL keywords and blocking spaces. This is a weak form of input validation and can be easily bypassed by an attacker.\n\nThe code converts the user input to uppercase and then removes the SQL keywords \"FROM\" and \"SELECT\". However, this approach is flawed because SQL is not case sensitive and an attacker can use lower case or mixed case SQL keywords to bypass this check. Also, the code checks if the user input contains a space and if it does, it rejects the input. This can also be bypassed by an attacker by using comments or other SQL syntax that does not require spaces.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nThe best way to prevent SQL Injection attacks is to use parameterized queries or prepared statements. This ensures that user input is always treated as literal data and not executable code. Also, it is recommended to use a web application firewall (WAF) that can detect and block SQL Injection attacks.\n\n## Source Code Fix\n\nHere is a recommended fix for the code using parameterized queries:\n\n```java\nString query = \"SELECT * FROM users WHERE userId = ?\";\nPreparedStatement stmt = connection.prepareStatement(query);\nstmt.setString(1, userId);\nResultSet rs = stmt.executeQuery();\n```\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code example requires the following library dependencies:\n\n- Java SQL library (java.sql.*)\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP SQL Injection Prevention Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/SQL_Injection_Prevention_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [CWE-89: Improper Neutralization of Special Elements used in an SQL Command ('SQL Injection')](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/89.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-89",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/89.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "8.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-89"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "4eb56178-acb8-3029-a1a8-2b7ae7a0280c",
              "name": "Vulnerability in Trust Redirection Based on Raw URL String Prefix Checks Instead of Host Validation",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThis vulnerability occurs when a Java application uses raw URL string prefix checks to validate the host of a URL, instead of using proper host validation methods. This can lead to trust redirection attacks, where an attacker can manipulate the URL to redirect users to a malicious site. The vulnerability is present in the code where it checks if the URL starts with \"https://webgoat.local\" or \"http://webgoat.local\". An attacker can bypass this check by using a URL like \"http://webgoat.local.evil.com\", which would pass the check but redirect the user to \"evil.com\".\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, the application should use proper host validation methods instead of raw URL string prefix checks. The application should parse the URL and validate the host against a whitelist of trusted hosts. \n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nHere is a recommended fix for the code:\n\n```java\n@RestController\n@AssignmentHints({\"openredirect.hint7\", \"openredirect.hint8\"})\npublic class OpenRedirectTask4 implements AssignmentEndpoint {\n\n  private static final Set<String> INTERNAL_HOSTS = Set.of(\"webgoat.local\", \"localhost\", \"127.0.0.1\");\n\n  @PostMapping(\"/OpenRedirect/task4\")\n  @ResponseBody\n  public AttackResult doubleDecode(@RequestParam(\"target\") String target) {\n    if (target == null || target.isBlank()) {\n      return failed(this).feedback(\"openredirect.failure4\").output(\"Empty value\").build();\n    }\n\n    // First decode (application does this)\n    String firstDecoded = URLDecoder.decode(target, StandardCharsets.UTF_8);\n\n    URI firstUri;\n    try {\n      firstUri = new URI(firstDecoded);\n    } catch (URISyntaxException e) {\n      return failed(this).feedback(\"openredirect.failure4\").output(\"Invalid URL after first decode\").build();\n    }\n\n    String firstHost = firstUri.getHost();\n    if (!INTERNAL_HOSTS.contains(firstHost)) {\n      return failed(this).feedback(\"openredirect.failure4\").output(\"Invalid host\").build();\n    }\n\n    // Rest of the code...\n  }\n}\n```\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code example requires the following library dependencies to execute properly:\n\n- Spring Boot Starter Web\n- Spring Boot Starter Validation\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP Unvalidated Redirects and Forwards Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Unvalidated_Redirects_and_Forwards_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [CWE-601: URL Redirection to Untrusted Site ('Open Redirect')](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/601.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-601",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/601.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "8.0",
                "tags": [
