            {
              "id": "700accfc-555b-3216-a4c2-31d13e7a4e2d",
              "name": "Hardcoded Credential Vulnerability in Authentication Logic",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nHardcoded Credential Vulnerability in Authentication Logic is a common security issue in Java programming. It occurs when developers embed sensitive information such as usernames, passwords, or keys directly into their source code. This practice is insecure because it exposes sensitive data to anyone who has access to the code. In the provided code snippet, the username \"CaptainJack\" and the password \"BlackPearl\" are hardcoded, which is a security risk.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nAvoid hardcoding sensitive information in your source code. Instead, use secure methods of storing and retrieving these values, such as environment variables or secure configuration files. \n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nInstead of hardcoding the values, you can retrieve them from environment variables:\n\n```java\nString username = System.getenv(\"USERNAME\");\nString password = System.getenv(\"PASSWORD\");\n\nif (username.equals(username) && password.equals(password)) {\n    // ...\n}\n```\n\nIn this example, the `USERNAME` and `PASSWORD` environment variables should be set in the environment where the application is running. This way, the sensitive data is not exposed in the source code.\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe provided code snippet does not require any additional library dependencies to execute properly.\n\n## OWASP Resources\n\n- [OWASP Top 10 2017 Category A2: Broken Authentication](https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/2017/A2_2017-Broken_Authentication)\n- [OWASP Authentication Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Authentication_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n\n## Common Weakness Enumeration (CWE)\n\n- [CWE-798: Use of Hard-coded Credentials](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/798.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-798",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/798.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "8.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-798"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "71604b5f-40bc-31ce-be01-006315f79f56",
              "name": "Direct JDBC Execution of Raw SQL in Method Parameter",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\n\"Direct Execution of Raw SQL through JDBC Method Parameter\" is a vulnerability that occurs when an application uses user-supplied data in a SQL query without properly validating or escaping it. This can lead to SQL Injection attacks where an attacker can manipulate the SQL query to access, modify, or delete data in the database.\n\nIn the provided code snippet, the `query` parameter is directly used in the `executeQuery` method of the `statement` object. If the `query` parameter contains user-supplied data, it can lead to SQL Injection attacks.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, it is recommended to use parameterized queries or prepared statements. These methods ensure that user-supplied data is always treated as literal values and not part of the SQL command. This effectively prevents SQL Injection attacks.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nHere is a recommended fix for the provided code snippet:\n\n```java\nString query = \"SELECT * FROM table WHERE column = ?\";\nPreparedStatement pstmt = connection.prepareStatement(query);\npstmt.setString(1, userInput);\nResultSet results = pstmt.executeQuery();\n```\n\nIn this code, `?` is a placeholder that is replaced by `userInput` using the `setString` method. This ensures that `userInput` is treated as a literal value and not part of the SQL command.\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe provided code snippet requires the following library dependencies:\n\n- `java.sql.Connection`\n- `java.sql.PreparedStatement`\n- `java.sql.ResultSet`\n\n## OWASP Resources\n\n- [OWASP SQL Injection Prevention Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/SQL_Injection_Prevention_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [OWASP Java Security Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Java_Security_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n\n## Common Weakness Enumeration (CWE)\n\n- [CWE-89: Improper Neutralization of Special Elements used in an SQL Command ('SQL Injection')](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/89.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-89",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/89.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "8.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-89"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "79928727-f668-346c-a619-4006fe3bbad9",
              "name": "Hardcoded Default Credentials Vulnerability in Authentication Logic",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nHardcoded Default Credentials Vulnerability in Authentication Logic is a common security issue in Java programming. This vulnerability occurs when developers hardcode default credentials into the application's authentication logic. This can lead to unauthorized access to the system if an attacker discovers these hardcoded credentials.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, avoid hardcoding credentials in your application's code. Instead, use secure methods of storing and retrieving credentials. For example, you can use environment variables, secure configuration files, or a secure credential storage system.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nHere is a recommended fix for the provided code:\n\n```java\n// Get credentials from a secure source instead of hardcoding\nString secureUsername = System.getenv(\"SECURE_USERNAME\");\nString securePassword = System.getenv(\"SECURE_PASSWORD\");\n\nif (secureUsername.equals(username.trim()) && securePassword.equals(password)) {\n    return success(this)\n        .feedback(\"securitymisconfiguration.task1.success\")\n        .output(\"User profile: staging admin (no MFA)\")\n        .build();\n}\n```\n\nIn this fix, we are retrieving the username and password from environment variables instead of using hardcoded values.\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code example does not provide enough context to determine the required library dependencies.\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP Top 10 - A2:2017-Broken Authentication](https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/2017/A2_2017-Broken_Authentication)\n- [CWE-798: Use of Hard-coded Credentials](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/798.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
