            {
              "id": "7a7f602f-6c4b-346b-8b18-2f44739ee4cb",
              "name": "\"Unsecured Default Session Middleware: Vulnerable to Cross-Site Scripting Attacks\"",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\n\"Unsecured Default Session Middleware: Vulnerable to Cross-Site Scripting Attacks\" is a vulnerability that can occur in Java web applications when session management is not properly secured. This can lead to Cross-Site Scripting (XSS) attacks, where an attacker injects malicious scripts into webpages viewed by other users. In this case, the vulnerability arises from the insecure handling of cookies.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, it is recommended to:\n\n1. Always validate and sanitize user input: This can prevent an attacker from injecting malicious scripts into your webpages.\n\n2. Use HTTPOnly cookies: This attribute prevents JavaScript from accessing the cookies, which can prevent XSS attacks.\n\n3. Use secure cookies: This attribute ensures that the cookies are only sent over HTTPS, which can prevent them from being intercepted.\n\n4. Implement Content Security Policy (CSP): This can prevent a wide range of XSS attacks by specifying which sources of content are valid.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nHere is a recommended fix for the given code:\n\n```java\nCookie cookie = new Cookie(\"access_token\", \"\");\ncookie.setHttpOnly(true);\ncookie.setSecure(true);\n```\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code example requires the following library:\n\n- javax.servlet.http.Cookie\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP XSS (Cross Site Scripting) Prevention Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Cross_Site_Scripting_Prevention_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [OWASP Java Encoder Project](https://owasp.org/www-project-java-encoder/)\n- [CWE-79: Improper Neutralization of Input During Web Page Generation ('Cross-site Scripting')](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/79.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-319",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/319.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "5.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-319"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "7c288fd9-fed4-3269-95a5-3f9b0bbb42a9",
              "name": "\"Use of Host Header in Constructing Password Reset or Email Links\"",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe \"Use of Host Header in Constructing Password Reset or Email Links\" vulnerability in Java programming language refers to a situation where an application uses the HTTP Host header to construct a URL within the application. This can be exploited by an attacker to poison the password reset or email links, leading to phishing attacks, session theft, or worse.\n\nThis vulnerability is particularly dangerous because the Host header is controlled by the client and can be manipulated to point to an arbitrary domain. If the application blindly trusts this header to construct URLs, it can lead to serious security issues.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, the application should not trust the Host header to construct URLs. Instead, it should use a trusted server name that is configured in the application or server settings. \n\nIf it's absolutely necessary to use the Host header, the application should validate it against a whitelist of trusted domains before using it to construct URLs.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nInstead of using the Host header to construct the reset link, use a trusted server name that is configured in the application or server settings. Here is an example of how to do this:\n\n```java\nString serverName = getServerNameFromConfig(); // Get the trusted server name from the config\nString resetLink = \"https://\" + serverName + \"/resetPassword?token=\" + token;\nsendMailToUser(email, serverName, resetLink);\n```\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe specific library dependencies required by the code example will depend on the specific Java framework and email library you are using. However, in general, you will need:\n\n- A Java web framework library (like Spring, Struts, etc.)\n- A Java email library (like JavaMail API)\n\n## OWASP Resources\n\n- [OWASP Unvalidated Redirects and Forwards Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Unvalidated_Redirects_and_Forwards_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [OWASP Java Security Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Java_Security_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n\n## Common Weakness Enumeration (CWE)\n\n- [CWE-601: URL Redirection to Untrusted Site ('Open Redirect')](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/601.html)\n- [CWE-346: Origin Validation Error](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/346.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-601",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/601.html"
                  },
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-346",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/346.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "8.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-601",
                  "CWE-346"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "7d52e729-2d31-3c48-9792-5c35db982cf6",
              "name": "\"Exposure of Server-Side Coupon and Promo Codes\"",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe \"Exposure of Server-Side Coupon and Promo Codes\" vulnerability refers to a situation where an application inadvertently exposes sensitive information, such as coupon or promo codes, to unauthorized users. In the provided Java code, the server-side coupon code is exposed to the client-side, which could potentially be exploited by malicious users.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, it is recommended to:\n\n- Avoid exposing sensitive information, such as coupon or promo codes, to the client-side.\n- Implement proper access control mechanisms to ensure that only authorized users can access sensitive information.\n- Use secure communication protocols, such as HTTPS, to protect sensitive information during transmission.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nThe following code snippet demonstrates how to fix the vulnerability:\n\n```java\n@GetMapping(value = \"/coupons/{code}\", produces = MediaType.APPLICATION_JSON_VALUE)\npublic ResponseEntity<CheckoutCode> getDiscountCode(@PathVariable String code, Principal principal) {\n  if (principal == null || !checkoutCodes.isAuthorized(principal.getName(), code)) {\n    return new ResponseEntity<>(HttpStatus.FORBIDDEN);\n  }\n  return ResponseEntity.ok(checkoutCodes.get(code).orElse(new CheckoutCode(\"no\", 0)));\n}\n\n@GetMapping(value = \"/coupons\", produces = MediaType.APPLICATION_JSON_VALUE)\npublic ResponseEntity<CheckoutCodes> all(Principal principal) {\n  if (principal == null || !checkoutCodes.isAuthorized(principal.getName())) {\n    return new ResponseEntity<>(HttpStatus.FORBIDDEN);\n  }\n  List<CheckoutCode> all = Lists.newArrayList();\n  all.addAll(this.checkoutCodes.getCodes());\n  return ResponseEntity.ok(new CheckoutCodes(all));\n}\n```\n\nIn this revised code, we have added a `Principal` parameter to the methods, which represents the currently authenticated user. We then check if the user is authorized to access the requested coupon code or all coupon codes. If the user is not authorized, we return a 403 Forbidden status code.\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code example requires the following library dependencies:\n\n- Spring Web\n- Google Guava\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP Top Ten: A2-Broken Authentication](https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/2017/A2_2017-Broken_Authentication)\n- [CWE-200: Information Exposure](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/200.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-200",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/200.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "5.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-200"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "7fc7160a-a366-38f9-b469-f24262f6a5ee",
              "name": "\"Host and Referer or Origin Header Comparison Used for CSRF Validation Instead of Anti-CSRF Token\"",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe vulnerability arises when the application relies on the Host and Referer or Origin headers for Cross-Site Request Forgery (CSRF) validation instead of using an Anti-CSRF token. The Host and Referer or Origin headers can be manipulated by an attacker, making the application susceptible to CSRF attacks. In the provided code, the application is checking if the Referer header is null, but it does not validate if the request is coming from a trusted source or not.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nThe best way to mitigate this vulnerability is to use Anti-CSRF tokens. The server should generate a unique token for every session (or for every individual request in more secure systems) and this token should be embedded within all forms and AJAX calls. When the server receives a request, it should check the validity of the Anti-CSRF token.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\n```java\nimport javax.servlet.http.HttpServletRequest;\nimport javax.servlet.http.HttpSession;\nimport org.apache.commons.lang.RandomStringUtils;\n\npublic class CSRFTokenGenerator {\n\n    public static String generate(HttpServletRequest request) {\n        HttpSession session = request.getSession(false);\n        String token = null;\n        if (null != session) {\n            token = (String) session.getAttribute(\"CSRF_TOKEN\");\n            if (null == token) {\n                token = RandomStringUtils.random(32, true, true);\n                session.setAttribute(\"CSRF_TOKEN\", token);\n            }\n        }\n        return token;\n    }\n}\n```\n\nIn the above code, a CSRF token is generated and stored in the session. This token should be embedded in all forms and AJAX calls. When the server receives a request, it should check the validity of the CSRF token.\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code example requires the following library dependencies:\n\n- javax.servlet-api\n- commons-lang\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP CSRF Prevention Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Cross-Site_Request_Forgery_Prevention_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [CWE-352: Cross-Site Request Forgery (CSRF)](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/352.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-352",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/352.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "8.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-352"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "89164205-100f-33f1-bf2c-dab53b8bcfca",
              "name": "Unrestricted User-Controlled Target Redirection Vulnerability",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nUnrestricted User-Controlled Target Redirection Vulnerability, also known as Open Redirect, is a security flaw that can occur in web applications, especially those written in Java. It allows an attacker to redirect a user to an arbitrary website of the attacker's choosing. This can be used in phishing attacks to trick users into visiting malicious websites without their knowledge.\n\nIn the provided code snippet, the application is redirecting the user to a URL that is being controlled by the user input. This is a security risk as it allows an attacker to control where the application redirects the user.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, you should avoid using user-controlled data to determine the destination of server-side redirects. If it is necessary to use user-controlled data, it should be validated to ensure it is safe. This can be done by maintaining a list of valid URLs to which the application can redirect, and only allowing redirection to URLs on this list.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nHere is a simple way to fix the vulnerability in the provided code snippet:\n\n```java\nList<String> validUrls = Arrays.asList(\"http://example.com\", \"http://example.org\");\n\nif (validUrls.contains(url)) {\n    return new ModelAndView(\"redirect:\" + url);\n} else {\n    // Handle invalid URL\n}\n```\n\nIn this code, we maintain a list of valid URLs and only allow redirection to URLs on this list.\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe provided code snippet requires the following library dependencies:\n\n- Spring Web MVC\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP Unvalidated Redirects and Forwards Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Unvalidated_Redirects_and_Forwards_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [CWE-601: URL Redirection to Untrusted Site ('Open Redirect')](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/601.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-601",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/601.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "8.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-601"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "8f745816-bbfc-3d0f-921a-9db7d342714d",
              "name": "Direct JDBC Execution of Raw SQL in Method Parameter Vulnerability",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\n\"Direct JDBC Execution of Raw SQL in Method Parameter Vulnerability\" is a security vulnerability in Java programming language that occurs when an application uses user-supplied data in a SQL query without properly validating or escaping it. This can lead to SQL Injection attacks where an attacker can manipulate the SQL query to access, modify or delete data in the database.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, it is recommended to use parameterized queries or prepared statements instead of concatenating user-supplied data directly into a SQL query. This ensures that user-supplied data is always treated as literal values and not part of the SQL command.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nInstead of:\n\n```java\nString query = \"UPDATE users SET password='\" + newPassword + \"' WHERE username='\" + username + \"'\";\nstatement.executeUpdate(query);\n```\n\nUse:\n\n```java\nString query = \"UPDATE users SET password=? WHERE username=?\";\nPreparedStatement pstmt = connection.prepareStatement(query);\npstmt.setString(1, newPassword);\npstmt.setString(2, username);\npstmt.executeUpdate();\n```\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code example requires the following library dependencies:\n\n- `java.sql.Connection`\n- `java.sql.PreparedStatement`\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP SQL Injection Prevention Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/SQL_Injection_Prevention_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [CWE-89: Improper Neutralization of Special Elements used in an SQL Command ('SQL Injection')](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/89.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-89",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/89.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "8.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-89"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "90617087-7eb3-34eb-8ca5-4716a67e0379",
              "name": "Username or Email-Based Password Reset or Recovery Vulnerability",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\n\"Username or Email-Based Password Reset or Recovery Vulnerability\" is a security vulnerability that arises when an application allows an attacker to reset or recover a user's password based on the username or email alone. This can lead to unauthorized access to the user's account. In the provided Java code, the password is simply the reverse of the username, which is a weak password policy and can be easily exploited by an attacker.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, it is recommended to implement a strong password policy. This includes:\n\n- Not allowing the password to be too similar to the username or email.\n- Requiring the password to be a certain length and to include a mix of letters, numbers, and special characters.\n- Not allowing common or easily guessable passwords.\n- Implementing a secure password reset or recovery process that involves multiple steps and requires the user to prove their identity.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nHere is a simple fix for the provided code:\n\n```java\nimport org.apache.commons.lang3.StringUtils;\n\n// ...\n\nif (username.equals(webGoatUsername)) {\n    String generatedPassword = generateSecurePassword();\n    if (StringUtils.equals(generatedPassword, password)) {\n        // ...\n    }\n}\n\n// ...\n\nprivate String generateSecurePassword() {\n    // Implement a method to generate a secure password\n}\n```\n\nIn this fix, a secure password is generated that is not based on the username. The `generateSecurePassword` method should implement a secure password generation algorithm.\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe provided code requires the following library:\n\n- Apache Commons Lang\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP Password Storage Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Password_Storage_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [OWASP Forgot Password Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Forgot_Password_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [CWE-640: Weak Password Recovery Mechanism for Forgotten Password](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/640.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-640",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/640.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "8.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-640"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "90c1577c-c040-32ce-acfc-970dd4af9b31",
              "name": "'jku' Header Claim JWT Vulnerability Allows Key Fetching from URL Without Visible Allowlist",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe 'jku' Header Claim JWT Vulnerability allows an attacker to specify a URL from which the application will fetch a JSON Web Key (JWK) to verify a JSON Web Token (JWT). If the application does not validate or restrict the URLs that can be used for the 'jku' header, an attacker can host a malicious JWK on a server they control and force the application to fetch it. This can lead to various attacks, including signature spoofing and potentially remote code execution.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, it is recommended to use a allowlist of trusted URLs for fetching JWKs. The application should reject any JWTs that specify a 'jku' header not in the allowlist. Additionally, it is recommended to use a secure and updated library for handling JWTs, and to follow best practices for JWT security.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\n```java\nSet<String> trustedUrls = new HashSet<>(Arrays.asList(\"https://trustedurl1\", \"https://trustedurl2\"));\n\nURL jkuUrl = new URL(jku.asString());\nif (!trustedUrls.contains(jkuUrl.getHost())) {\n    throw new SecurityException(\"Untrusted JKU URL: \" + jkuUrl);\n}\n\nvar jwkProvider = new JwkProviderBuilder(jkuUrl).build();\n```\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code example requires the following library dependencies:\n\n- `auth0`: For the `JwkProviderBuilder` class.\n- `java.net`: For the `URL` class.\n- `java.util`: For the `HashSet` and `Arrays` classes.\n\n## OWASP Resources\n\n- [JWT Cheat Sheet for Java](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/JSON_Web_Token_for_Java_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [Insecure JWT Storage](https://owasp.org/www-project-web-security-testing-guide/latest/4-Web_Application_Security_Testing/06-Session_Management_Testing/10-Testing_JSON_Web_Tokens.html)\n\n## Common Weakness Enumeration (CWE)\n\n- [CWE-295: Improper Certificate Validation](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/295.html)\n- [CWE-346: Origin Validation Error](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/346.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-295",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/295.html"
                  },
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-346",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/346.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "8.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-295",
                  "CWE-346"
                ]
              }
