            {
              "id": "97153270-115f-3a36-a551-78a0c319bc0e",
              "name": "Unencoded HTML Response Data Vulnerability",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe \"Unencoded HTML Response Data Vulnerability\" in Java is a type of Cross-Site Scripting (XSS) vulnerability. It occurs when an application includes untrusted data in a new HTML page without proper HTML encoding, and sends it to a user's web browser. This can allow an attacker to inject malicious scripts into the web page, which can then be executed by the user's browser.\n\nIn the provided code, the vulnerability lies in the concatenation of `field1` to the `cart` string without any sanitization or encoding. If `field1` contains any malicious scripts, they will be included in the HTML response and executed by the user's browser.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, you should always HTML encode untrusted data before including it in an HTML response. This will ensure that any scripts or HTML tags in the data are treated as plain text and not executed by the user's browser.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nYou can use the `StringEscapeUtils.escapeHtml4()` method from the Apache Commons Text library to HTML encode `field1` before appending it to `cart`:\n\n```java\nimport org.apache.commons.text.StringEscapeUtils;\n\n// ...\n\ncart.append(\"<p>We have charged credit card:\" + StringEscapeUtils.escapeHtml4(field1) + \"<br />\");\n```\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code example requires the following library dependencies:\n\n- Apache Commons Text\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP Cross-Site Scripting (XSS)](https://owasp.org/www-community/attacks/xss/)\n- [OWASP XSS (Cross Site Scripting) Prevention Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Cross_Site_Scripting_Prevention_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [CWE-79: Improper Neutralization of Input During Web Page Generation ('Cross-site Scripting')](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/79.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-79",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/79.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "8.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-79"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "97cae28f-4ac9-31ab-8ba2-b46c64d0265e",
              "name": "\"Unsecured Actuator Endpoint Defined in Application Code\"",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe vulnerability \"Unsecured Actuator Endpoint Defined in Application Code\" refers to the exposure of sensitive information through an unsecured endpoint in a Java application. In the provided code, the endpoint `/SecurityMisconfiguration/task3/actuator/env` is exposing sensitive information such as the system API key and environment details. This can lead to unauthorized access and misuse of the application.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, it is recommended to secure the actuator endpoints. This can be achieved by:\n\n- Limiting the exposure of sensitive information through the endpoints.\n- Implementing authentication and authorization mechanisms to restrict access to the endpoints.\n- Regularly reviewing and updating the security configurations.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nThe following code snippet provides a fix for the vulnerability by adding a security configuration to the endpoint:\n\n```java\nimport org.springframework.http.MediaType;\nimport org.springframework.web.bind.annotation.GetMapping;\nimport org.springframework.security.access.prepost.PreAuthorize;\n\n@GetMapping(\n      value = \"/SecurityMisconfiguration/task3/actuator/env\",\n      produces = MediaType.APPLICATION_JSON_VALUE)\n@PreAuthorize(\"hasRole('ADMIN')\")\npublic Map<String, Object> actuatorEnv() {\n    return Map.of(\n        \"name\", \"webgoat-staging\",\n        \"profiles\", new String[] {\"staging\", \"debug\"},\n        \"systemApiKey\", LEAKED_API_KEY,\n        \"features\", Map.of(\"betaUi\", true, \"payments\", false));\n}\n```\n\nIn this code, the `@PreAuthorize` annotation is used to ensure that only users with the 'ADMIN' role can access the endpoint.\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code requires the following library dependencies:\n\n- Spring Web\n- Spring Security\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP Top 10 - Security Misconfiguration](https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/2017/A6_2017-Security_Misconfiguration)\n- [CWE-276: Incorrect Default Permissions](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/276.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-276",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/276.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "5.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-276"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "97e8efd5-6883-38f4-ba9f-899da2a6a81e",
              "name": "Host and Referer/Origin header comparison used for CSRF protection instead of anti-CSRF token.",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe vulnerability in question is related to Cross-Site Request Forgery (CSRF) protection. In the provided code, the application is trying to prevent CSRF attacks by comparing the \"Host\" and \"Referer\" HTTP headers. However, this method is not reliable because these headers can be manipulated by an attacker. \n\nThe \"Host\" header indicates the domain name and port number of the server to which the request is being sent. The \"Referer\" header indicates the address of the webpage that linked to the resource being requested. By comparing these two headers, the application is trying to ensure that the request is coming from the same origin. However, an attacker can spoof these headers and trick the application into accepting a malicious request.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nThe most effective way to prevent CSRF attacks is to use anti-CSRF tokens. These are random, unique values that are associated with a user's session and included in every state-changing request. The server checks the token in each request and rejects the request if the token is not valid. This ensures that only legitimate requests from the user are accepted.\n\nIn addition to using anti-CSRF tokens, it's also important to implement other security measures such as validating and sanitizing all user input, using secure cookies, and implementing proper error handling.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nThe code should be modified to use anti-CSRF tokens. Here is a basic example of how this could be done:\n\n```java\n// Generate a new anti-CSRF token and store it in the user's session\nString antiCsrfToken = generateNewToken();\nrequest.getSession().setAttribute(\"antiCsrfToken\", antiCsrfToken);\n\n// Include the anti-CSRF token in every state-changing request\nString form = \"<form action=\\\"/submit\\\" method=\\\"post\\\">\";\nform += \"<input type=\\\"hidden\\\" name=\\\"antiCsrfToken\\\" value=\\\"\" + antiCsrfToken + \"\\\">\";\nform += \"</form>\";\n\n// Check the anti-CSRF token in each request\nString submittedToken = request.getParameter(\"antiCsrfToken\");\nString sessionToken = (String) request.getSession().getAttribute(\"antiCsrfToken\");\nif (submittedToken == null || !submittedToken.equals(sessionToken)) {\n  return failed(this).feedback(\"csrf-you-forgot-something\").build();\n}\n```\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe provided code does not specify any library dependencies. However, it appears to be using the Java Servlet API, which is included in the Java Enterprise Edition (Java EE) or Jakarta EE platform.\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP CSRF Prevention Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Cross-Site_Request_Forgery_Prevention_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [CWE-352: Cross-Site Request Forgery (CSRF)](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/352.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-352",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/352.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "8.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-352"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "99161671-a964-3ac6-84fd-1c1fbe5fa169",
              "name": "\"Sensitive PII or Compensation Data Exposed in HTTP Endpoint Query Response\"",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe code above is vulnerable to data exposure. It exposes sensitive Personally Identifiable Information (PII) or compensation data in an HTTP endpoint query response. This is a serious security issue as it can lead to unauthorized access to sensitive data. The data is exposed in the HTTP response of the `clientSideFiltering/salaries` endpoint, which returns a list of employees with their sensitive details like UserID, FirstName, LastName, SSN (Social Security Number), and Salary.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, you should never expose sensitive data in HTTP responses. Instead, sensitive data should be securely stored and encrypted, and only authorized users should be able to access it. You should also implement proper access control mechanisms to ensure that only authorized users can access sensitive data.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nA potential fix for this vulnerability would be to remove the sensitive data from the HTTP response. If the sensitive data is necessary for the functionality of the application, consider implementing a secure method of data retrieval, such as using secure tokens or implementing proper access controls.\n\n```java\n@GetMapping(\"clientSideFiltering/salaries\")\n@ResponseBody\npublic List<Map<String, Object>> invoke() {\n  // ... existing code ...\n\n  sb.append(\"/Employees/Employee/UserID | \");\n  sb.append(\"/Employees/Employee/FirstName | \");\n  sb.append(\"/Employees/Employee/LastName | \");\n\n  // ... existing code ...\n}\n```\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code example requires the following library dependencies to execute properly:\n\n- Spring Web (`org.springframework:spring-web`)\n- Java XML Path (`javax.xml.xpath`)\n- Java I/O (`java.io`)\n- Java XML DOM (`org.w3c.dom`)\n- Java XML (`javax.xml`)\n- Java Utility (`java.util`)\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP Top 10-2017 A3-Sensitive Data Exposure](https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/2017/A3_2017-Sensitive_Data_Exposure)\n- [CWE-200: Information Exposure](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/200.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-200",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/200.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "5.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-200"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "997d943f-05bc-349b-bd9a-ebd0dde133dc",
              "name": "Unspecified HTTP Method in 'RequestMapping' Annotation Potentially Vulnerable to CSRF Attacks",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe `@RequestMapping` annotation in Spring MVC is used to map web requests onto specific handler classes and/or handler methods. If the HTTP method is not specified in the `@RequestMapping` annotation, it means that the endpoint is open to all HTTP methods (GET, POST, PUT, DELETE, etc.). This can potentially make the application vulnerable to Cross-Site Request Forgery (CSRF) attacks.\n\nIn a CSRF attack, an attacker tricks a victim into performing actions on their behalf on a web application in which they're authenticated. With a little help of social engineering (like sending a link via email or chat), an attacker may trick the users of a web application into executing actions of the attacker's choosing.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, it is recommended to specify the HTTP method in the `@RequestMapping` annotation. This can be done by using the `method` attribute of the `@RequestMapping` annotation and setting it to the appropriate `RequestMethod` enum (e.g., `RequestMethod.GET`, `RequestMethod.POST`, etc.).\n\nIn addition, it is also recommended to enable CSRF protection in your Spring application. Spring Security provides built-in CSRF protection that can be enabled in your Spring Security configuration.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nHere is how you can specify the HTTP method in the `@RequestMapping` annotation:\n\n```java\nimport org.springframework.http.MediaType;\nimport org.springframework.web.bind.annotation.RequestMapping;\nimport org.springframework.web.bind.annotation.RequestMethod;\n\n@RequestMapping(path = \"/crypto/signing/getprivate\", method = RequestMethod.GET, produces = MediaType.TEXT_HTML_VALUE)\n```\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe following libraries are required by the code example:\n\n- Spring Web MVC\n- Spring Security\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP CSRF Prevention Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Cross-Site_Request_Forgery_Prevention_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [OWASP Top 10-2017 A8-Insecure Deserialization](https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/2017/A8_2017-Insecure_Deserialization)\n- [CWE-352: Cross-Site Request Forgery (CSRF)](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/352.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-352",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/352.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "5.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-352"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "99e96353-6596-3524-bc66-428e593739c7",
              "name": "Unspecified HTTP Method in 'RequestMapping' Annotation Potentially Vulnerable to CSRF Attacks",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe `@RequestMapping` annotation in Spring MVC is used to map web requests onto specific handler classes and handler methods. When the HTTP method is not specified in the `@RequestMapping` annotation, it means that the mapped method will respond to all HTTP methods (GET, POST, PUT, DELETE, etc.). This can potentially make the application vulnerable to Cross-Site Request Forgery (CSRF) attacks.\n\nIn a CSRF attack, an attacker tricks a victim into performing actions on their behalf on a web application in which they're authenticated. With the help of social engineering (like sending a link via email or chat), an attacker may trick the users of a web application into executing actions of the attacker's choosing.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, it is recommended to specify the HTTP method in the `@RequestMapping` annotation. This way, the mapped method will only respond to the specified HTTP method(s), reducing the attack surface.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nHere is an example of how to specify the HTTP method in the `@RequestMapping` annotation:\n\n```java\n@RequestMapping(path = URL_LESSONMENU_MVC, method = RequestMethod.GET, produces = \"application/json\")\n```\n\nIn this example, the mapped method will only respond to HTTP GET requests.\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code example requires the following library dependencies:\n\n- Spring Web MVC\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP CSRF Prevention Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Cross-Site_Request_Forgery_Prevention_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [CWE-352: Cross-Site Request Forgery (CSRF)](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/352.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-352",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/352.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "5.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-352"
                ]
              }
