            {
              "id": "ce4af615-c618-3693-9094-7015e59c9176",
              "name": "Potential SQL Injection Detected: Use Prepared Statements for Sanitization",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\n\"Potential SQL Injection Detected: Use Prepared Statements for Sanitization\" is a vulnerability that occurs when an application includes untrusted data in a SQL query. This can allow an attacker to manipulate the query, leading to unauthorized data access, data corruption, or data loss. In Java, this vulnerability can occur when using the `execute` method of a `Statement` object with a string that includes untrusted data.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, use Prepared Statements or Parameterized Queries. These methods ensure that untrusted data is properly escaped, preventing it from being interpreted as part of the SQL query. Avoid using string concatenation to build SQL queries.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nInstead of:\n\n```java\nString queryInjection = \"SELECT * FROM users WHERE name = '\" + userName + \"'\";\nstatement.execute(queryInjection);\n```\n\nUse:\n\n```java\nString query = \"SELECT * FROM users WHERE name = ?\";\nPreparedStatement preparedStatement = connection.prepareStatement(query);\npreparedStatement.setString(1, userName);\npreparedStatement.executeQuery();\n```\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code example requires the following library dependencies:\n\n- `java.sql.Connection`\n- `java.sql.PreparedStatement`\n\n## OWASP Resources\n\n- [OWASP SQL Injection Prevention Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/SQL_Injection_Prevention_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [OWASP Java Encoder library](https://owasp.org/www-project-java-encoder/)\n\n## Common Weakness Enumeration (CWE)\n\n- [CWE-89: Improper Neutralization of Special Elements used in an SQL Command ('SQL Injection')](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/89.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-89",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/89.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "8.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-89"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "d2bf7399-d551-3bfa-8ab9-0be6950a54e9",
              "name": "Host and Referer/Origin header comparison used for CSRF protection instead of anti-CSRF token.",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe vulnerability arises from the comparison of the Host and Referer/Origin headers for Cross-Site Request Forgery (CSRF) protection instead of using an anti-CSRF token. The Host header is controlled by the user and can be manipulated, while the Referer/Origin header can be spoofed or removed by the user or by network devices or software. This makes the application susceptible to CSRF attacks.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nThe best way to mitigate this vulnerability is to use anti-CSRF tokens. These tokens should be unique per user session, large random values, and they should be securely generated. They should be inserted within all state changing forms and verified at the server side. \n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\n```java\n// Generate a secure random CSRF token\nSecureRandom sr = SecureRandom.getInstance(\"SHA1PRNG\");\nString csrfToken = Integer.toString(sr.nextInt());\n\n// Store the CSRF token in the user's session\nuserSessionData.setValue(\"csrfToken\", csrfToken);\n\n// Insert the CSRF token in the form\nresponse.put(\"csrfToken\", csrfToken);\n\n// Verify the CSRF token at the server side\nif (csrfToken.equals(req.getParameter(\"csrfToken\"))) {\n    // The CSRF token is valid, process the request\n} else {\n    // The CSRF token is invalid, reject the request\n}\n```\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code example does not appear to require any specific library dependencies.\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP CSRF Prevention Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Cross-Site_Request_Forgery_Prevention_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [CWE-352: Cross-Site Request Forgery (CSRF)](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/352.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-352",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/352.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "8.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-352"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "d70aab63-7f1f-329b-91bf-80275e38b637",
              "name": "Unspecified HTTP Method in 'RequestMapping' Annotation Potentially Vulnerable to CSRF Attacks",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nIn Java, the `@RequestMapping` annotation is used to map web requests onto specific handler classes and/or handler methods. If the HTTP method is not specified in the `@RequestMapping` annotation, it can potentially make the application vulnerable to Cross-Site Request Forgery (CSRF) attacks. CSRF is an attack that tricks the victim into submitting a malicious request. It uses the identity and privileges of the victim to perform an undesired function on their behalf.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, it is recommended to always specify the HTTP method in the `@RequestMapping` annotation. This can be done by using the `method` attribute of the `@RequestMapping` annotation and setting it to one of the `RequestMethod` enumerations (GET, POST, PUT, DELETE, etc.). This will ensure that the handler method is only invoked for requests with the specified HTTP method, reducing the attack surface for CSRF attacks.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nHere is an example of how to specify the HTTP method in the `@RequestMapping` annotation:\n\n```java\nimport org.springframework.web.bind.annotation.RequestMapping;\nimport org.springframework.web.bind.annotation.RequestMethod;\n\n@RequestMapping(value = \"/endpoint\", method = RequestMethod.POST)\npublic void handlePostRequest() {\n    // handler code\n}\n```\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe above code example requires the following library dependencies:\n\n- Spring Web MVC (`spring-webmvc`)\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP CSRF Prevention Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Cross-Site_Request_Forgery_Prevention_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [OWASP Top 10-2017 A8-Insecure Deserialization](https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/2017/A8_2017-Insecure_Deserialization)\n\n## Matching CWE\n\n- [CWE-352: Cross-Site Request Forgery (CSRF)](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/352.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-352",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/352.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "5.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-352"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "e0d56bb8-4ec7-3ae1-bce4-65591418f08b",
              "name": "Unnormalized Path Vulnerability",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nUnnormalized Path Vulnerability in Java occurs when the application does not properly neutralize special elements within the paths of filenames that can cause the application to access resources outside of the restricted, expected directory. This can lead to unauthorized access to files and directories, potentially leading to information disclosure, data corruption, or execution of arbitrary code.\n\nIn the provided code, the vulnerability lies in the line where the name of the ZipEntry is directly used to create a new File object. If the ZipEntry name includes path traversal characters (like \"../\"), it could lead to files being written outside of the intended directory.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, it is recommended to normalize the path before using it and check if it's still within the expected directory. Normalizing the path will resolve any \".\" or \"..\" sequences. After normalization, the path should be checked to ensure it's still within the expected directory.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\n```java\nvar uploadedZipFile = tmpZipDirectory.resolve(file.getOriginalFilename());\nFileCopyUtils.copy(file.getBytes(), uploadedZipFile.toFile());\n\nZipFile zip = new ZipFile(uploadedZipFile.toFile());\nEnumeration<? extends ZipEntry> entries = zip.entries();\nwhile (entries.hasMoreElements()) {\n  ZipEntry e = entries.nextElement();\n  File f = new File(tmpZipDirectory.toFile(), e.getName()).getCanonicalFile();\n  if (!f.getPath().startsWith(tmpZipDirectory.toFile().getCanonicalPath())) {\n    throw new IllegalStateException(\"File is outside extraction directory\");\n  }\n  InputStream is = zip.getInputStream(e);\n  Files.copy(is, f.toPath(), StandardCopyOption.REPLACE_EXISTING);\n}\n```\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\n- `java.nio.file`\n- `java.util.zip`\n- `java.io`\n- `org.springframework.util.FileCopyUtils`\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP Path Traversal](https://owasp.org/www-community/attacks/Path_Traversal)\n- [CWE-22: Improper Limitation of a Pathname to a Restricted Directory ('Path Traversal')](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/22.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-22",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/22.html"
                  }
                ],
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "security-severity": "8.0",
                "tags": [
                  "security",
                  "CWE-22"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "e1f43931-4d9a-3e46-84c4-13ee865eb7f1",
              "name": "Non-Allowlisted External Host Redirect Vulnerability in URL Handling",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe \"Non-Allowlisted External Host Redirect Vulnerability in URL Handling\" is a security vulnerability in Java programming language that allows an attacker to redirect users to malicious websites. This vulnerability occurs when a web application accepts a user-controlled input that specifies a link to an external site, and uses that link in a Redirect. If the application does not validate the input correctly, an attacker can craft a URL within the application that causes the redirection to an arbitrary external domain.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, it is recommended to avoid using user input to determine the destination of server-side redirects. If this is not possible, ensure that the supplied value is valid, appropriate for the application, and authorized for the user. It is also recommended to use allowlist validation on the user input. \n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nIn the provided code, the vulnerability can be fixed by adding a check to ensure that the host of the URL is in the allowlist. Here is the fixed code:\n\n```java\n@RestController\n@AssignmentHints({\"openredirect.hint3\", \"openredirect.hint4\"})\npublic class OpenRedirectTask2 implements AssignmentEndpoint {\n\n  private static final Set<String> ALLOWED = Set.of(\"webgoat.local\", \"webgoat.org\", \"localhost\");\n\n  @PostMapping(\"/OpenRedirect/task2\")\n  @ResponseBody\n  public AttackResult simulate(@RequestParam(\"url\") String url) {\n    if (url == null || url.isBlank()) {\n      return failed(this).feedback(\"openredirect.failure2\").output(\"Empty value\").build();\n    }\n    if (!url.contains(\"webgoat\")) {\n      return failed(this).feedback(\"openredirect.failure2\").output(\"Must contain 'webgoat'\").build();\n    }\n    if (!(url.startsWith(\"http://\") || url.startsWith(\"https://\"))) {\n      return failed(this).feedback(\"openredirect.failure2\").output(\"Needs absolute URL with http/https\").build();\n    }\n    try {\n      URI u = new URI(url);\n      String host = u.getHost();\n      if (host == null) {\n        return failed(this).feedback(\"openredirect.failure2\").output(\"Could not parse host\").build();\n      }\n      if (!ALLOWED.contains(host.toLowerCase())) {\n        return failed(this).feedback(\"openredirect.failure2\").output(\"Host not allowed\").build();\n      }\n      return success(this);\n    } catch (URISyntaxException e) {\n      return failed(this).feedback(\"openredirect.failure2\").output(\"Invalid URL\").build();\n    }\n  }\n}\n```\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code example requires the following library dependencies to execute properly:\n\n- Spring Boot Starter Web\n- Spring Boot Starter Test\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP Unvalidated Redirects and Forwards Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Unvalidated_Redirects_and_Forwards_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [CWE-601: URL Redirection to Untrusted Site ('Open Redirect')](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/601.html)"
              },
