            {
              "id": "f2969a84-f931-3b93-83b1-d4add2abbfb0",
              "name": "\"XML Injection Vulnerability with Disabled Security\"",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nXML Injection is a type of attack that occurs when an attacker injects malicious XML code into a XML document or stream that is being processed by an application. This can lead to various types of attacks such as Denial of Service (DoS), data theft, or code execution. In Java, this vulnerability can occur when XML parsing is done without proper security measures.\n\nIn the provided code snippet, the `parseXml` method is called with a `false` parameter, which indicates that security is disabled. This makes the application vulnerable to XML Injection attacks.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, you should always enable security when parsing XML. This can be done by setting the second parameter of the `parseXml` method to `true`. Additionally, you should also validate and sanitize all user inputs to ensure that they do not contain malicious XML code.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nHere is a recommended fix for the provided code snippet:\n\n```java\nvar comment = comments.parseXml(commentStr, true);\n```\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code snippet does not provide enough context to determine the exact library dependencies. However, XML parsing in Java typically requires the following libraries:\n\n- `javax.xml.parsers`\n- `org.w3c.dom`\n- `org.xml.sax`\n\n## References\n\n- [CWE-611: Improper Restriction of XML External Entity Reference ('XXE')](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/611.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-611",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/611.html"
